As generative AI tools become increasingly accessible, educators face the challenge of guiding students to use them ethically and effectively without compromising core learning outcomes. In our CS1 courses, we have implemented a structured framework that encourages responsible AI use while reinforcing critical thinking and problem-solving skills. Students are introduced to clear boundaries for AI-assisted work, including guidelines for classroom use and assignments. To promote deeper engagement, we incorporate peer-based code explanation and evaluation exercises, where students articulate their understanding and assess each other's work. This approach fosters accountability, collaboration, and metacognitive awareness, helping students distinguish between leveraging AI as a tool and relying on it as a crutch. Our preliminary observations suggest that students gain confidence in both their technical and communicative abilities while developing a nuanced understanding of AI's role in computing education.